    "markdown": "**Top of mind:** The human-data market's new pecking order is now common knowledge: Menlo Ventures' Deedy Das published a viral map of 50+ startups selling data and RL environments to the labs — roughly $8.5B in combined revenue and ~$100B in valuation, over 75% of it sitting with Scale, Surge, Mercor and Handshake — just as Mercor moves to close $500M at a $20B valuation. Meanwhile Gemini 3.5 Pro is reportedly targeted for July 17, which would kick off another heavy eval and post-training cycle at Google.\n\n## Competitor moves\n\n- **The training-data market map goes viral: ~$8.5B revenue, ~$100B valuation, four firms holding 75%+.** Menlo Ventures' Deedy Das catalogued the 50+ startups selling data and RL environments to big AI labs; the takeaway for everyone outside Scale, Surge, Mercor and Handshake is that differentiation now comes from specialization — domains, modalities, RL environments — rather than headcount. Worth studying where you sit on it. [X](https://x.com/deedydas/status/2076124392711696455)\n- **Mercor's $500M-at-$20B round heads toward a close this month.** Follow-on coverage through Monday confirms a term sheet in hand at a valuation that doubled in nine months on a $2B annualized run-rate, with the Deeptune acquisition signalling RL environments as the next margin pool. Comps for every expert-network and RLHF vendor just moved again. [Silicon Valley Investclub](https://siliconvalleyinvestclub.com/2026/07/13/mercor-to-raise-500-million-at-a-20-billion-valuation/), [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-07-09/ai-training-startup-mercor-discusses-20-billion-valuation), [Yahoo Finance](https://finance.yahoo.com/technology/ai/articles/mercor-funding-talks-show-ai-195703187.html)\n\n## New projects & opportunities\n\n- **HCL is getting into the AI datacenter business.** The Register reports India's tech-services giant is moving into AI datacenters — more AI infrastructure inside India means more domestic model training and deployment work, and a bigger local buyer base for data, evaluation and post-training services. [The Register](https://www.theregister.com/off-prem/2026/07/14/indias-tech-services-giant-hcl-is-getting-into-the-ai-datacenter-business/5270827)\n\n## Frontier lab movements\n\n- **Gemini 3.5 Pro reportedly lands July 17 after a ground-up rebuild — though Google hasn't confirmed a thing.** Leaks point to a scrapped 2.5 Pro architecture, a 2M-token context window and a \"Deep Think\" reasoning layer, with Google Search reportedly already running entirely on Gemini 3.5 Flash; as of July 13 there is no model card, pricing page or API listing. A launch this week would trigger a fresh wave of eval, red-teaming and post-training data demand from one of the sector's biggest buyers. [TechTimes](https://www.techtimes.com/articles/320308/20260713/gemini-35-pro-targets-july-17-after-full-rebuild-every-spec-remains-unconfirmed.htm), [BigGo Finance](https://finance.biggo.com/news/6f0c6bb2-795f-4c57-9d09-6db691d7638a)\n\n## Research papers\n\n- **Pretrain on document images, not extracted text, says a Shanghai AI Lab-affiliated team.** \"Scalable Visual Pretraining for Language Intelligence\" (Yiming Zhang, Kai Chen and 14 coauthors) shows visual pretraining on the same corpora consistently beats text-only pretraining — figures, equations and layout carry signal that OCR throws away. If this holds, visually-rich document corpora become first-class training data, reshaping document sourcing and curation work. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.09657), [Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.09657)\n- **Test-time training on long contexts only works if you pick the right spans.** Self-Guided TTT (Xinyu Zhu et al.) shows adaptation on random spans hurts long-context performance while model-selected evidence spans lift LongBench-v2/Pro accuracy by up to 15% relative — more evidence that span-level relevance judgments and hard long-context evals are where human data adds value. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.09415), [Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.09415)\n- **A 31-author consortium ships a sovereign, open-source German/English foundation model.** Featured on Monday's Hugging Face Daily Papers, it is the latest proof that the sovereign-AI wave is producing real models — every national program like it needs local-language pretraining data, SFT and culturally grounded evals, a template India-focused suppliers should be pitching against. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.09424), [Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.09424)\n\n## Leadership movements\n\n- Nothing notable today.\n"
