    "markdown": "**Top of mind:** Mercor is in talks to raise ~$500M at a roughly $20B valuation — double its October price — in the same week a wave of contractor-misclassification lawsuits hit Mercor, Surge, Scale and Handshake. The expert-data category is being priced at ~10x revenue just as its 1099 labor model faces its first serious legal test in California; compliance-clean managed delivery is turning into a sales asset. Separately, Apple's trade-secret suit against OpenAI (filed July 10) moves the AI talent war into the courtroom.\n\n## Competitor moves\n\n- **Mercor in talks for ~$500M at a ~$20B valuation; ARR hit $2B in June (July 9).** The raise would double the $10B mark from its October Series C; run-rate revenue doubled in four months, and Mercor also acquired agent-training startup Deeptune. With Surge reportedly seeking ~$15B and Scale priced at $29B, expert-network data supply now trades at ~10x revenue — expect labs to push back on rates and rivals to raise fast behind it. [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-07-09/ai-training-startup-mercor-discusses-20-billion-valuation) · [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/07/09/mercor-is-in-talks-for-a-20b-valuation/) · [Forbes](https://www.forbes.com/sites/richardnieva/2026/07/09/mercor-fundraise/)\n- **Misclassification lawsuits pile up against Mercor, Surge, Scale and Handshake (spotlighted July 10-11).** A class action says Mercor misclassified 30,000+ experts as independent contractors; Surge faces a parallel California suit, and Law.com named AI-trainer suits a top litigation trend to watch. If US contractor pools get reclassified, per-task economics break — an opening for vendors running employed, compliance-clean delivery teams (an India managed-services strength) to win risk-averse lab procurement. [Law.com](https://www.law.com/2026/07/10/litigation-trends-to-watch-lawsuits-center-on-ai-trainers-surveillance-pricing-and-last-mile-delivery-drivers/) · [Law360](https://www.law360.com/employment-authority/articles/2475907/ai-startup-misclassified-30k-workers-suit-says) · [Bloomberg Law](https://news.bloomberglaw.com/litigation/ai-training-firm-surge-ai-hit-with-worker-misclassification-suit) · [NYT via GV Wire](https://gvwire.com/2026/07/11/the-work-of-helping-ai-destroy-work/)\n\n## New projects & opportunities\n\n- **Humanoid-robot capital wave: Agility files a $2.5B SPAC, Unitree cleared for its Shanghai IPO, Tesla converts a production line for Optimus (week of July 10).** Public-market scrutiny forces real performance numbers, which means demonstration data, teleoperation hours and sim-environment evaluation at scale — robotics data collection is shaping up as the next big services line, and India's engineering talent pool fits teleop and QA hubs well. [Unrot](https://unrot.co/blogs/today-top-10-ai-news-july-12-2026)\n- **HHS will point ChatGPT at ~$2.1T of Medicare/Medicaid audit reports across all 50 states (July 10).** One of the largest government deployments of a commercial model yet, with funding-withholding consequences — the mandatory human-review layer (domain-expert QA, error analysis, hallucination auditing) is exactly the adjacent services line data vendors can sell. [Unrot](https://unrot.co/blogs/today-top-10-ai-news-july-12-2026) · [BuildFastWithAI](https://www.buildfastwithai.com/blogs/ai-news-today-july-12-2026)\n\n## Frontier lab movements\n\n- **Apple sues OpenAI and two former employees for trade-secret theft (July 10).** The complaint alleges coordinated extraction of hardware secrets via 400+ ex-Apple hires, interview practices and a laptop-based breach, aimed at OpenAI's io device push. Talent-war litigation raises the cost of poaching-led capability building — labs may lean more on external expert networks and data vendors rather than risk more mass-hire lawsuits. [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/07/10/apple-openai-lawsuit-trade-secrets.html) · [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/07/10/apple-sues-openai-trade-secret-theft) · [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/07/10/apple-openai-lawsuit-trade-secrets-theft-allegations/)\n- **Google Search now serves fully AI-generated results pages via Gemini 3.5 Flash (as of July 10).** The default ten-blue-links page is gone; citations sit inside the generated answer. Web-scale grounding, citation-accuracy and answer-quality evaluation becomes a permanent, high-volume data need — and content owners' licensing leverage just shifted. [Unrot](https://unrot.co/blogs/today-top-10-ai-news-july-12-2026) · [The Agency Journal](https://theagencyjournal.com/google-search-just-got-a-massive-glow-up-how-gemini-3-5-flash-is-rewriting-the-rules/) · [ZoomBangla](https://inews.zoombangla.com/google-search-gemini-3-5-flash-july-2026/)\n- **GPT-5.6 after 48 hours: Terra roughly matches frontier coding at half price; Sol hits ~750 tok/s on Cerebras (July 11).** With Gemini 3.5 Pro leaked for July 17, three labs land frontier releases within nine days and benchmark headroom is compressing — differentiation shifts to harder private evals and hard-case data, the highest-margin work in this category. [Unrot](https://unrot.co/blogs/today-top-10-ai-news-july-12-2026) · [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/07/09/openai-launches-its-new-family-of-models-with-gpt-5-6/)\n- **Meta plans to double total compute by 2027; custom Iris chip enters production in September (July 10).** A 1GW Alberta data center and Samsung supply deals signal the next model-generation cycle — each compute build-out precedes fresh SFT, RL and eval data procurement. [Unrot](https://unrot.co/blogs/today-top-10-ai-news-july-12-2026) · [BigGo](https://finance.biggo.com/news/2e5bf076-8041-48cb-96d9-89a8b7799461)\n\n## Research papers\n\n- **UltraX: refining pretraining data at scale with adaptive programmatic editing (arXiv, July 10).** Xinlong Zhao, Dongsheng Liu, Hengyu Zhao et al. propose programmatically editing existing corpora to extract more quality as raw-web scaling plateaus — data refinement, not just collection, is becoming a distinct and sellable pipeline stage. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08646)\n- **UniClawBench: a universal benchmark for proactive agents on real-world tasks (arXiv, July 10).** Zhekai Chen, Chengqi Duan, Kaiyue Sun et al. standardize evaluation of agents operating everyday tools — every serious agent benchmark expands demand for human-built task environments, gold trajectories and graders. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08768)\n- **The Illusion of Equivalency: quantization changes model behavior even when accuracy looks flat (arXiv, July 10).** Baha Rababah, Cuneyt Gurcan Akcora and Carson K. Leung show perplexity and accuracy mask systematic output shifts, arguing for distributional-fidelity testing — a fresh eval-services niche as labs ship compressed and on-device variants. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08734)\n\n## Leadership movements\n\n- **Fidji Simo steps back from OpenAI's No. 2 role to part-time advisor (July 9).** Product and business execution consolidates under president Greg Brockman heading into OpenAI's IPO window — procurement priorities at the industry's biggest data buyer often shift with the org chart. [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/07/09/openai-exec-fidji-simo-says-she-will-step-down-and-transition-to-part-time-advisor.html) · [The Verge](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/963738/openai-fidji-simo-steps-down-ceo-advisor)\n- **Marc Andreessen named co-lead of the Federal Reserve's first AI task force (July 11).** A policy-side appointment rather than a lab hire, but its measurement of AI's labor-market impact will shape the regulatory climate around AI work — including how offshore data work is counted and governed. [Unrot](https://unrot.co/blogs/today-top-10-ai-news-july-12-2026) · [BuildFastWithAI](https://www.buildfastwithai.com/blogs/ai-news-today-july-12-2026)"
